Add Python generator

I have fixed some compilation errors and rebased against the

author: Dmitry Shachnev
commit_message:
Convert only ASCII letters to lowercase

This is needed to match C behavior and make the testsuite pass.

author: Olly Betts
commit_message:
Use iconv by default

It's significantly faster than python, and the inline python code
doesn't work with python 3.

Provide 'iconv.py' - a simple iconv replacement written in python which
can be used if iconv isn't available.

author: Olly Betts
commit_message:
Eliminate range-check implementation for groupings

It was removed from the C generator 10 years ago, isn't used for any of
the existing algorithms, and it doesn't seem likely it would be - the
grouping would have to consist entirely of a contiguous block of
Unicode code-points.

author: Olly Betts
commit_message:
[python] Implement "go grouping" optimisation

`go` or `gopast` followed by a grouping or `non` and a grouping is
a common idiom which we already optimise when generating C code.
Implement in a similar way for Python, which speeds up "make
check_python" by about 4%.

author: Dmitry Shachnev
commit_message:
[python] Remove caching layer

If there are not many words to stem, the caching layer negatively affects
performance.

Those who need to stem many words and care about performance should
consider using PyStemmer.

author: Olly Betts
commit_message:
stemwords.py: Use argv.pop(0) to unshift elements

Removing and retrieving in one function is cleaner, and avoids bugs
(such as us not actually removing the argument for -c, though we
also currently ignore options we don't understand so this the
processing of -c's argument as an option would typically not cause
a problem).

author: Olly Betts
commit_message:
[python] Handle stemmer names with underscore

Previously the code generated in __init__.py didn't convert to camel
case correctly if there was an underscore.

author: Olly Betts
commit_message:
[python] Add classifier to indicate Python 3.3 support

In doc/libstemmer_python_README we say "Python 3 (>= 3.3) is supported"
(which is because we generate literal strings with a `u` prefix) so
update the classifier list to include it for consistency.

See #192

author: Olly Betts
commit_message:
[python] Specify python_requires

Indicate to install tools that the generated code won't work with Python
3.0.x, 3.1.x and 3.2.x (due to use of `u"foo"` string literals).

Closes #192 and #191, opened by Andreas Maier.
